description: A special pair of mussels was found, one with both unique shape and some hitch-hiking neighbors! One of these was a pink barnacle, with grooved sides and a central hole. These were washed up along the tar-oozing Rocky Shore coastline.

description: A special pair of mussels was found, one with both unique shape and some hitch-hiking neighbors! The mussel shells were distributed throughout the sandy, slippery rocks. The bivalve shells were ovular, silvery, and dark. These were a very common species of this Rocky Shore.
name: Mytilus californianus

description: The dried formation was extremely intriguing, and at the time I had absolutely no clue which species this was associated with! The pale, twisting tubular formations were abundantly strewn on the Rocky Shore beaches.

description: Red/purple hues, the lineup of small holes, and the polished, silvery insides made this shell a pure abalone indeed. Found near the oozing tar deposits, these were rare along the Rocky Shore coastline.
